1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. dxc5 {This move order is not
particularly dangerous, but Black should know how to face it.} (5. e3) (5. e4
$5 {was seen in a few games of Mamedyarov. It's not totally harmless, but
Black should be fine with correct play.} dxe4 6. Bb5+ (6. d5 {is also possible.
The position resembles sort of a reversed Albin Gambit.} Nf6 ({The greedy} 6...
f5 $5 {also seems playable. After} 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Nh3 $44 {White seems to have
nice compensation for the pawn, but Black is not worse either.}) 7. Bf4 ({
Black is fine in the line} 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bb5+ Bd7 $1 9. d6 Bxb5 10. Nxb5 ({Or} 
10. dxe7 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Bd3 12. f3 Nbd7 $11) 10... Qa5+ 11. Nc3 h6 12. Bh4 Bd8
13. Nge2 O-O 14. O-O Nbd7 $11 {Black remains a pawn up, and the passed pawn is
safely blocked.}) 7... a6 (7... Bd6 {direct is possible, but the position after
} 8. Bb5+ $1 Kf8 9. Qd2 {can be a bit tricky.}) 8. d6 $2 {White's position
might look great at first sight: the d6-pawn prevents the development of the
f8-bishop and next White can develop in an active way. However, the situation
is quite the opposite. After} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 9. Nge2 Be6 10. Ng3 Nd4 11.
Ncxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bf5 $19 {Black is basically winning.}) ({In some games
White players tried to go for a quick assault with} 6. Bc4 $2 cxd4 7. Qb3 {
but this bold idea backfires badly due to} Nf6 $1 8. Bxf7+ Ke7 {and White's
position is already collapsing. In one game he decided to grab some material
with} 9. Nd5+ Kxf7 10. Nc7+ {but after} Kg6 11. Nxa8 Na6 $19 {[%csl Ra8] ;
Nadanian,A (2413) -Godena, M (2485) EU-ch 1st Saint Vincent 2000 (8) 0-1 Black
has a clearly winning position.}) 6... Bd7 7. Nge2 {White aims a quick
development.} (7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Nge2 Nc6 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bb4 $11 {is
simply harmless for Black.}) 7... Nf6 8. O-O (8. Bg5 $2 {can be met by} Bxb5 9.
Nxb5 Qa5+ 10. Nec3 a6 $1 {when I like Black's chances already, for example:}
11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Na3 Nc6 13. d5 Nd4 14. O-O f5 $17) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 10.
Nf5 {White gets some pressure, which nevertheless is not enough to pose
serious problems for Black.} O-O 11. Bxd7 Nbxd7 12. Bg5 $6 (12. Nd5 {White
could've regained the pawn by means of} Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Nf6 14. Qxb7 Bc5 $11) ({
Or} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qg4 Bf6 14. Qxe4 Nc5 $11) 12... Re8 13. Qa4 $2 {Han,Y 
(2286) -Agmanov,Z (2459) Paracin op-A 15th 2022 (7) 1-0 Now after the simple}
Bf8 14. Rad1 Qc7 $17 {Black would keep a pawn up and a comfortable game.}) 5...
d4 6. Na4 $5 {This was played by Carlsen and seems an ambitious option to me.}
(6. Ne4 {is more popular. After} Nc6 7. Nf3 {we've transposed to Chapter 3.} (
7. e3 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 {is fine for Black.})) 6... b5 $1 {An important
idea that should be remembered. Instead of regaining the pawn, Black is ready
to sacrifice it in order to exploit the misplaced Na4.} (6... Bxc5 $2 {is
playable with the inclusion of Nf3/Nc6, but in this position, it leaves Black
in trouble after} 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Qxc5 9. Rc1 Qf5 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Nf3 Qd5
12. e3 dxe3 13. Bxe3 $16 {[%cal Gf1c4] and White's initiative is already very
serious.}) (6... Nc6 $2 {is also bad in view of} 7. a3 $1 $16 {[%cal Yb2b4]})
7. cxb6 ({In one game White tried to be creative with} 7. e3 $2 bxa4 8. Qf3 $2
(8. exd4 $142 $17) 8... Bxc5 9. Qxa8 {but after} Bb4+ $19 {Valsecchi,A (2491)
-Sirosh,I (2405) Online Olym Div2 C rapid 2020 (5.1) 0-1 Black had a crushing
attack.}) 7... axb6 {[%csl Ra4] Now White needs to do something about the
knight on the edge as b6-b5 is already a threat.} 8. b3 {is the most played,
preparing the manoeuvre Nb2-d3.} (8. e3 {is another option.} Bd7 9. b3 b5 ({
I also like} 9... Nf6 $5 {as accepting the second pawn turns out to be very
bad for White:} 10. Qxd4 $2 Nc6 11. Qd1 Ne4 $19 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gf8b4] and Black
has a crushing initiative.}) 10. Nb2 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 dxe3 $1 {a nice tactical
detail.} 12. Bxb4 (12. fxe3 {keeps the pawn, but after} Ba3 13. Nd3 Nf6 14. Nf3
Nc6 15. Be2 O-O 16. O-O Qb6 $44 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Gd7f5] Black has a
comfortable position, with easy moves and at least enough compensation for the
pawn.}) 12... Qh4 $1 13. Nd3 exf2+ 14. Nxf2 Qxb4+ 15. Qd2 Nc6 $11 {and Black
has comfortably equalized.}) (8. e4 {avoids the idea seen after 8.e3, but
still leaves Black with a nice position.} Bd7 ({In case of} 8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2
Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Rxa4 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxa4 Bxa4 13. Nf3 $14 {White probably
keeps better chances.}) 9. b3 Nf6 10. Bd3 ({But not} 10. Qxd4 $2 Nc6 $19 {
as Black's initiative develops very quickly and strongly.}) 10... b5 11. Nb2
Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Ba3 13. Qb1 Nc6 $1 {Black just keeps developing the pieces in the
most active way.} 14. Ne2 ({Once more, accepting the second pawn looks risky:} 
14. Bxb5 $2 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4]} 15. f3 Ne5 $1 16. Be2 Be6 17. Nd3 Nfd7 $19 {
[%cal Yf7f5] Despite having two pawns up, White's position is too cramped and
underdeveloped, and Black is ready to open more lines with f7-f5, followed by
a devastating attack.}) 14... O-O 15. O-O Ne5 {[%csl Rb2,Rd3][%cal Ga3b2]} 16.
Nd1 Re8 {Black has nice compensation for the pawn here, the superior
development and White's cramped position speak for itself. A possible
variation is} 17. f3 (17. Nxd4 Bc5 $36 {looks dangerous for White: there are
too many pieces on the d-file.}) (17. Ng3 Nfg4 $1 18. h3 Qh4 $1 $19 {is
another nice example of how things can go out of control for White.}) 17... Qb6
18. Nf2 b4 {[%cal Gd7b5,Ge5d3]} 19. Re1 Nxd3 20. Nxd3 Bb5 21. Nef4 Rad8 $44 {
The position is roughly balanced. White can finish the development in the next
moves by exchanging bishops on c1, but the passed pawn and strong play in the
centre give Black decent compensation for the pawn.}) 8... b5 ({Both} 8... Nf6
{and}) (8... Nc6 {are more popular, but I like the text as it is more direct.})
9. Nb2 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 {Carlsen,M (2847) -Artemiev,V (2704) Aimchess US Rapid KO
2021 (3.12) 1-0 Now,} Bc3 $1 {is an improvement, after which Black is already
playing for an advantage.} (10... Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Nf6 {was how Artemiev played,
and it was also enough to equalize.}) 11. Bxc3 ({In case of the natural reply} 
11. Qc2 {Black has the strong continuation} Nf6 $1 12. Bxc3 dxc3 13. Qxc3 O-O {
when White is two pawns up now, but it's Black who plays for the advantage due
to the better development and dangerous initiative. For example:} 14. Nd3 Nd5
15. Qd2 Bf5 16. Nf3 Bxd3 $1 ({Or} 16... Qf6 17. Qb2 Qxb2 18. Nxb2 Nb4 $36) 17.
exd3 Qf6 18. d4 Re8+ 19. Kd1 (19. Be2 Nf4 $19) 19... b4 $17 {and White is
clearly in trouble.}) 11... dxc3 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Despite entering the endgame
down a pawn, Black has better chances in this position.} 13. Nd3 ({Black is
also better in case of} 13. Nd1 b4 14. e4 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ge6b3] as there is no
adequate defence against Bxb3.}) (13. Rd1+ Kc7 14. Rc1 {might look like a
clever idea but after} Rxa2 15. Rxc3+ Nc6 16. Nd3 Nge7 {White remains under
pressure, for example:} 17. g3 Kb6 18. Bg2 Nd4 $17) 13... Nc6 14. e3 Nge7 {
Black's next moves are easy and good: we just need to complete the development
and mobilize our pieces in the most effective way. On the other hand, White is
behind in development and lacks a clear way of mobilizing his own forces. On
the top, Black's passed pawn might be a powerful asset. The following
variations provide some idea of how the game could develop from here:} 15. Nf3
(15. Ne2 b4 16. Rd1 Kc7 17. a4 Rd8 18. Nec1 Ra5 19. Be2 Rad5 $17 {and Black
keeps an annoying pressure.}) 15... Kc7 16. Be2 Rd8 17. O-O Bf5 18. Rfd1 ({If} 
18. Nde5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 b4 $19 {things look very bad for White.}) 18... c2 19.
Rd2 Kb6 20. Kf1 Bxd3 21. Bxd3 Rxa2 $1 22. Rc1 Nb4 23. Nd4 Nxd3 24. Rxd3 Nc6 $1
