g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 {To be honest, as a 1.d4 player the Tarrasch Variation always
seemed a bit dubious to me. Despite it has been a dangerous weapon in the
hands of Kasparov in his Candidates matches and is still employed by some
Grandmasters, White's position always seemed a bit easier to me, and I would
be happy if all my opponents played 3...c5. That being said, I must confess
that I was a bit shocked a few years ago when I saw the always inventive
Russian GM Daniil Dubov taking the Black side in the Tarrasch. In this
position, Dubov went for the sideline} cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 Bc5 $1 {and the
Tarrasch was suddenly back in the tournaments. Of course, the line was always
there and was played a few times by strong players, but the theoretical
discussion becomes much more serious when a top-level player steps in. Also,
it should be noted that Dubov's first games in this line showed many
interesting ideas for Black, with a modern approach that soon attracted other
players on making their theoretical contributions as well. Therefore, it seems
fair to me to call this line "Dubov's Tarrasch" :)} 9. Nxc6 {Let's start with
the exchange of knights, a thematic operation in IQP positions. White's idea
is to continue with Na4 followed by either Be3-Rc1 or Qc2 at some point,
establishing a strong grip on the d4/c5 squares, after which Black's position
would be a bit unpleasant and White gets an easier game. However, in this line
we already see a nice difference in Black's favour: Instead of having a
passive bishop on e7, like in the classic Tarrasch lines, now our bishop is
actively placed on the g1-a7 diagonal, making White's plan much harder to
accomplish.} ({Also, in this chapter I would like to show two sidelines:} 9.
