1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. e3 {In order to make this database as complete
as possible, as well as offer you a reliable repertoire against 1.d4, I would
like to finish it by examining lines in which White doesn't tries to refute
the concept of the Tarrasch, instead looking for less forcing positions with
e3. I should say that this is a solid and completely playable option. It often
leads to a strategic fight with chances and interesting ideas for both sides,
and I could make a whole database about these positions. Still, I'll try to
offer a practical way of solving Black's opening problems.} ({Another option
is to start with} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. e3 {keeping the possibility of isolating the
d5-pawn at some point.} ({In case of} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 {I suggest the less
exploited continuation} cxd4 $5 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {looking for active play in the
spirit of the Dubov's Tarrasch.} 8. Be2 ({Another possible variation is} 8. Nb3
Bb4 9. Bd2 Nf6 10. Nb5 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Ne4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc8e6] when
Black has a typically good IQP position, with space and active play.}) 8... Nf6
9. O-O O-O 10. Bf3 {[%cal Gd4b3] Black has many ways to keep a good position
here, for example:} Ne5 11. b3 Nxf3+ 12. Nxf3 b6 13. Bb2 Re8 14. Ne2 Ba6 $11 {
with a balanced game.}) 5... cxd4 $5 {Perhaps this is a small drawback for
White in this move order.} 6. exd4 (6. Qxd4 {avoids a symmetric structure but
allows a comfortable development for Black.} Nf6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Qd3 {Aronian,L 
(2781) -Vidit,S (2726) Skilling op Prelim rapid 2020 (2) 1-0} g6 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gf8g7,Gc8f5] a new and interesting idea, preparing to develop both
bishops on active positions.} 9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 {Now Black can
continue with} Qe7 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8d8] with a nice development. In case of} 12.
Nxd5 {we get very good compensation for the pawn, for example:} Nxd5 13. Qxd5
Rd8 14. Qb5 Rxd1+ 15. Bxd1 Be6 16. Bd2 Rd8 $44 {and Black is very active.})
6... Nf6 7. Nf3 Nc6 {In such a symmetric structure, White's only hope is to
exploit the advantage of the first move to pose some pressure on Black's
position. However, the practice has shown that that is not enough to get an
advantage.} 8. Bb5 $5 {White can consider changing the structure by exchanging
on c6 sometimes.} ({If} 8. Bd3 Bg4 $1 {the pin prevents White from playing for
an advantage.} 9. O-O Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Be2 Ne4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rc1 Rc8 14.
Re1 Bf6 $11 {Ali Marandi,C (2546) -Grabinsky,A (2363) Charlotte op 2020 (3) 1/
2-1/2 and Black is ok.}) 8... Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 (10. h3 {was played by
Carlsen in a recent game but after} h6 11. Re1 Bf5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Gd8b6] ;
Carlsen, M (2865) -Praggnanandhaa, R (2612) Airthings Masters Prelim rapid
2022 (8) 0-1 Black simply had a comfortable game, with easy development.})
10... Bg4 $1 11. Bxc6 ({The retreat} 11. Be2 {was seen in a recent game.} Re8
12. h3 {Mamedyarov,S (2759) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2766) Zagreb SuperUnited Blitz
2022 (13) 0-1} Bxf3 $146 13. Bxf3 h6 {seems good enough to avoid any problem
for Black. For example:} 14. Be3 Bc7 15. Re1 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8] with a
balanced game.}) (11. Nxd5 $2 {is obviously bad due to} Bxh2+ 12. Kxh2 Qxd5 13.
Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Ne5 Qd6 $15 {Lintchevski,D (2517) -Matlakov,M (2691) Titled
