that in case of} 16. exd4 Nxd4 17. b4 Qc7 {[%csl Yh2] Black wins an important
tempo.} 18. g3 Rad8 $11 {and Black is fine.}) 11... Bh5 12. Be2 {White has to
deal with this pin sooner or later.} O-O 13. b3 a6 {Black prepares the typical
attacking set-up with Bc7-Qd6.} ({Now} 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Be5 15. Bb2 Qa5 {
is simply met by} 16. a3 $1 $16 {[%cal Yb3b4] which secures a clear advantage
for White since the pawn won't be attacked on h2 anymore.}) 14. Bb2 Re8 15. Rc1
Bc7 16. Nh4 {A typical idea for White in such positions is to force favourable
exchanges.} Bg6 ({The seemingly strong idea} 16... Qd6 17. g3 Rxe3 $2 {is
refuted by} 18. Nf5 $1 $18) 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Bf3 {Shankland,S (2718) -Giri,A 
(2761) Chessable Masters Prelim rapid 2022 (11) 1/2-1/2 The way Giri played in
the game was fine, but now} Qd6 19. g3 ({But not} 19. Re1 $4 d4 $1 $19 {
and Black wins.}) 19... Rxe3 $1 {could be seriously considered. The correct
reply for White now is} 20. Na4 $1 (20. fxe3 $4 Qxg3+ 21. Bg2 Qh2+ 22. Kf2 Bg3+
$19) 20... Ree8 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 22. Bxd5 Rad8 23. Qf3 $11 {with an equal game.})
5... a6 $5 {I've always liked this move, as it seems a clever way of
exploiting the first move in Black's favour.} (5... Nc6 {is the most played,
keeping the symmetry. I like the text simply because it's more flexible.}) 6.
cxd5 {Now it seems that White's best option is to release the tension in the
centre.} ({The flexible} 6. a3 {is a good idea when Black plays 5...Nc6, but
here doesn't work so well in view of} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 Bb7 {[%cal Gb8d7]
when Black's position seems a bit more harmonious, as the knight can be
developed to d7. On the other hand, the white knight is passive and often
blocks the way of other pieces on c3. Black usually gets a good game without
problems in this line.} 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 (10. d5 exd5 11. Nxd5 c4 $1 $15 {
is more pleasant for Black.}) (10. e4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 O-O 13. f3 Qe7
$11 {Kozul,Z (2613) -Marin,M (2539) EU-ch blitz Tallinn 2016 (19) 0-1 was also
fine for Black.}) 10... Bd6 11. Rd1 Qb8 {Black has already equalized. In case
of careless play, White can even face some problems. The best way of
continuing the development here is} 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. b4 Ncd7 14. h3 O-O 15.
Bb2 Nb6 16. Nd2 {when White keeps the weak squares on his camp under control
and has a solid position. On the other hand, Black's position seems very
comfortable. The "problem" of the Ra8 can be solved by means of the nice idea}
Ra7 $5 {[%cal Gb7a8,Ga7c7,Gf8c8,Gf8d8]}) (6. dxc5 {only helps Black, in my
opinion, especially considering that in the main line we are forced to spend
one more tempo to develop the bishop.} Bxc5 7. a3 O-O 8. b4 Be7 $1 {The right
retreat.} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bb2 a5 $1 {[%csl Ya3,Yb4] The point on Black's 8th
move: White is forced to give some squares on the queenside.} 11. b5 Be6 {
[%csl Yc4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Ga8c8] ;Aravindh, C (2580) -Wagner, D (2558) Biel
MTO op 51st 2018 (7) 0-1 Black has the simple plan of Nbd7-b6 followed by Rc8,
with a solid position. In the long term, the weaknesses on White's queenside
can be a serious problem.}) 6... exd5 7. Be2 (7. g3 $5 {was tried in a few
games. White intends to castle first, then to play dxc5 and start to attack
the isolated pawn, when the bishop will be nicely placed on g2. Fortunately,
Black has a strong idea to avoid this plan.} Nc6 8. Bg2 {Here it's important
to remember} c4 $1 {changing the structure. In normal Tarrasch positions this
move allows White to undermine Black's structure with ideas like Ne5 or b2-b3,
but here the presence of the white pawn on e3 makes a big difference.} 9. O-O (
9. Ne5 Bb4 10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {transposes.}) 9... Bb4 $1 {This active
bishop move forces White to prepare the breakthrough b2-b3 and at the same
time initiates Black's play on the light squares.} 10. Ne5 {White continues in
a typical way.} ({Another option is} 10. Bd2 O-O 11. b3 {when I like} Bxc3 12.
Bxc3 Ne4 13. Qc2 b5 $11 {with a solid position for Black.}) 10... O-O 11. Bd2 {
Otherwise White is unable to undermine Black's queenside with b2-b3.} Re8 12.
Nxc6 (12. f4 $2 {is simply bad for White in view of} Bxc3 $1 13. Bxc3 Bf5 $17 {
[%csl Re4][%cal Gf5e4]}) 12... bxc6 13. b3 {With the pawn on e2 we could
safely talk about a small advantage for White. In this position, however,
Black achieves excellent counterplay by exploiting the weaknesses of the light
squares.} a5 $1 (13... Bxc3 $5 {was Dubov's solution and also has worked
nicely.} 14. Bxc3 Ne4 15. Rc1 a5 $1 16. bxc4 Ba6 17. f3 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Bxc4 19.
Rf2 Qg5 20. Qc1 h5 $5 $36 {Carlsen,M (2862) -Dubov,D (2702) Airthings Masters
KO rapid 2020 (1.13) 0-1 and even the World Champion was unable to hold
Black's initiative.}) 14. Qc2 {Carlsen has experienced this position with both
colours.} ({His game as Black went} 14. bxc4 Ba6 15. Qc2 Bxc4 16. Rfb1 {
and now he followed Dubov's recipe:} Bxc3 $1 17. Bxc3 Ne4 18. Be1 h5 $1 19. Qd1
h4 $36 {Artemiev, V (2704) -Carlsen, M (2847) Aimchess US Rapid KO 2021 (3.11)
0-1 The tension on the kingside doesn't look so dangerous by now, but it's in
fact very unpleasant for White. I remember being very impressed by the way how
Magnus handled the initiative in this game. It's a nice instructive model for
anyone who wants to play these positions with Black pieces.}) 14... cxb3 {
Releasing the tension is usually good for White, but Black has a different
set-up in mind.} ({In another game he decided to keep the tension with} 14...
Ba6 15. Rfd1 {Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2652) -Perunovic,M (2604) Lisbon Portugal
op 2017 (7) 1-0 Now we can improve Black's play by means of} Bxc3 {preparing
the typical plan Ne4-h5-h4. White can try to make it harder by} 16. Qxc3 $5 {
[%csl Ya5] but even then} Ne4 $1 17. Qxa5 Qf6 {seems an interesting idea for
Black. For example:} 18. Be1 c3 $1 {[%cal Ga6e2]} 19. Qc7 c2 20. Rdc1 Bd3 $44 {
with nice compensation for the pawn.}) 15. axb3 g6 16. Rfc1 Bf5 17. Qd1 Qd6 18.
Ra2 (18. Na4 {directly allows} Ba3 19. Rc3 Bb4 $11) 18... h5 $1 {Don't miss to
advance your h-pawn!} 19. Na4 h4 $132 {Carlsen,M (2845) -Mamedyarov,S (2790)
Gashimov Memorial 6th 2019 (5) 1/2-1/2 and Black was able to keep the balance
by exploiting the counterplay on the kingside.}) 7... Nc6 8. O-O Bd6 9. dxc5 {
White usually waits for Black to move the dark-squared bishop to play this
move, but we shouldn't be afraid of losing this tempo.} ({In case of} 9. b3 {
Black can play} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 $5 11. Nf3 Be6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rc1 Rad8 {
[%cal Gf8e8,Gf6e4] with a good position.}) 9... Bxc5 {We have a very typical
IQP position on the board. The structure ensures a strategic battle rich in
ideas for both sides. Talking from Black's perspective, I think this is the
best version we could get of an IQP. Black is able to develop all pieces
actively and play for the initiative, which is very important in such
positions. For White, the typical plans are to exploit the weak squares around
the d5-pawn, trying to establish a firm blockade on d4, followed by long-term
pressure against the isolated pawn. Let's see some practical examples of how
both sides can develop their respective plans.} 10. b3 ({Another option is to
seize space on the queenside with} 10. a3 O-O 11. b4 Ba7 {[%cal Gd5d4] Keeping
an eye on the breakthrough d5-d4.} 12. Bb2 (12. b5 $5 {is often played as a
way of fighting against the d5-d4 advance. However, after} axb5 13. Nxb5 Bb6
14. Bb2 Ne4 {I don't think that b4-b5 has improved White's chances. Black
still has a solid position and now the Ra8 is also taking part in the game.
The following game took a natural path:} 15. Rc1 Re8 {[%cal Ge4f2]} 16. Nbd4
Bd7 17. Qb3 $6 {This move allows Black to change the structure with} Nxd4 18.
Bxd4 Bxd4 19. exd4 Bc6 $11 {Grecescu,G (2423) -Lysyj,I (2595) EU-ch 9th
Plovdiv 2008 (5) 0-1 when Black's position is already a bit more pleasant,
since the white pawns are easier to attack.}) 12... Be6 ({The immediate} 12...
d4 $5 13. exd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bf3 {allows White to maintain some
pressure, although it should be playable as well.}) 13. Rc1 ({Now} 13. b5 {
can be answered by} Na5 $5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga8c8] showing another drawback of
the advance b4-b5.}) ({If} 13. Na4 {Black has} Ne4 {with similar ideas as in
the main line.}) 13... d4 $1 {with one more piece developed this advance works
nicely to solve Black's problems.} 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Bf3 Rb8 {
and Black is ok, for instance:} 17. Qc2 Ng4 $1 18. Rcd1 Qh4 19. h3 Ne5 20. Be4
Rfd8 $11) 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Ba7 $1 {A nice prophylactic move. Besides being
safe from attacks by the enemy pieces on a7, the bishop can be manoeuvred to
the b8-h2 diagonal at the right moment in order to force weaknesses on White's
kingside.} (11... d4 $4 {obviously doesn't work now due to} 12. Na4 {which is
already an example of how better placed this bishop is on a7.}) 12. Rc1 {
A logical developing move which prepares White's plan of exploiting the
squares d4 and c5.} (12. Na4 Ne4 13. Rc1 (13. Nd4 {is always met by} Qg5 $1 {
like in the main line.}) 13... Re8 {transposes.}) (12. Qd3 {aiming to increase
the pressure on the d-file is more direct. Still, this plan doesn't seem so
dangerous for Black.} Be6 13. Rfd1 Qe7 14. Rd2 Rad8 15. Rad1 {White has put
maximum pressure over the d-file, but his queen is simply misplaced on d3.
Black was aware of that detail and exploited it by means of} Bg4 16. Qb1 Bxf3
17. Bxf3 d4 $1 18. exd4 Nxd4 $36 {L'Ami, E (2565) -Sokolov, I (2676) NED-ch61
Hilversum 2006 (4) 0-1 and the initiative is already in Black's hands.}) ({
The set-up} 12. Qc2 Qe7 13. Rad1 {was seen in some games.} Rd8 14. Na4 {
Fier,A (2573) -Mekhitarian,K (2487) BRA-ch 78th Campinas 2011 (9) 1-0 White
goes for the most logical plan.} ({In case of other moves like} 14. Rfe1 {
Black simply develops with a comfortable game:} Be6 15. h3 Rac8 16. Qb1 Qb4 $5
$11 {[%cal Yd5d4] with the advance d5-d4 coming soon.}) 14... Be6 {was still
possible, for example:} 15. Nd4 Rac8 16. Nxe6 (16. Qb1 $2 {leaves White in
trouble after} Nxd4 17. Bxd4 b5 $1 18. Nb2 Ne4 $17 {[%cal Ga7d4,Ge4c3,Ge7a3]
with a imminent invasion of Black's pieces on the queenside.}) 16... fxe6 17.
Nc3 {when Black has a pleasant choice between taking the initiative
immediately by means of} d4 $5 $36 ({Or making some useful moves to improve
his pieces before going for direct action, for instance:} 17... Kh8 $5 18. Qb1
Rf8 19. h3 Rcd8 20. Bd3 e5 $15 {[%cal Ga7b8,Ye5e4,Yd5d4] in both cases Back
has an easier game.})) 12... Re8 13. Na4 (13. h3 {was seen in a recent game.
White aims to improve his pieces by means of a thematic regrouping with
Bd3-Ne2-Ned4. Still, I like how Caruana faced this plan, just completing his
own development in a natural way:} Qd6 14. Bd3 Bd7 15. Ne2 Rad8 16. Ned4 {
White has just reached the desired set-up, but with all his forces centralized,
Black is ready to develop his own actions on the kingside.} Ne4 17. Qe2 ({
A safe continuation for White was} 17. Nxc6 Bxc6 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Qxd6 Rxd6
20. Nd4 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 $11) 17... Bb8 $1 18. Rfd1 Qg6 {Both sides have played
natural moves, but Black's position seems already more pleasant due to the
pressure on the kingside.} 19. Nh4 $2 {A serious mistake in an already
difficult situation.} Nxd4 $1 20. Bxd4 Qh6 21. Nf3 Bxh3 $1 $19 {Nihal,S (2652)
-Caruana,F (2800) FIDE Grand Swiss 2021 (2) 1/2-1/2 Black is totally winning,
although White managed to escape by a miracle. Still, I think this game shows
in a very instructive way how to handle positions with an IQP.}) 13... Ne4 {
This is an almost automatic response when the white knight goes to a4. It also
creates the threat of Nxf2 in some positions.} 14. Nd4 ({If} 14. Bxa6 $5 {
Black has the response} Bxe3) ({In case of} 14. Nc3 Be6 {Miezis, N (2524)
-Sadler, M (2653) Olympiad-41 Tromsoe 2014 (4.4) 0-1 Black just continues his
development with a good position.}) 14... Qg5 $1 {Black has an active position
and the attack on the kingside seems very promising. White should be very
careful now and play the prophylactic} 15. Kh1 $1 {stepping out of tactical
tricks.} ({Practice has shown that other moves are inferior and help Black.
Let's check some practical examples:} 15. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 16. Bd4 (16. Rxc6 $4 {
is much worse in view of} Nxf2 $1 17. Rxf2 Qxe3 $19 {and Black wins.}) 16...
Bh3 17. Bf3 Re6 $1 {[%cal Ge6g6] A typical manoeuvre to increase the pressure,
which already forces material gains for Black.} 18. Kh1 $2 Rg6 19. g3 ({
Maybe White realized too late that} 19. gxh3 $4 {is refuted by} Qg1+ $1 20.
Rxg1 Nxf2#) 19... Bxf1 $19 {Cori,J (2686) -Georgiadis,N (2514) Biel 52nd 2019 
(7) 0-1}) (15. Bf3 {was played once. Black achieved a winning position by
simple play now:} Ne5 16. Kh1 Qh4 17. g3 Qh6 $19 {[%cal Gc8h3] ;Rychagov,A 
(2549) -Izoria, Z (2602) Speed Chess GP2 blitz 2021 (3) 0-1 and White's
position seems horrible.}) (15. f4 $2 {Anton Guijarro, D (2703) -Studer, N 
(2580) Biel rapid 53rd 2020 (4) 0-1 is a typical defensive resource in some
positions, but doesn't work well here as White isn't able to continue with
Nxc6 and Bd4, establishing a strong control in the centre. The simplest
continuation now was} Qe7 16. Bf3 Bd7 17. Re1 Rac8 {when even in case of} 18.
Nxc6 Rxc6 19. Rxc6 (19. Qxd5 Rxc1 20. Bxc1 Bc6 21. Qd3 Qf6 $17) 19... Bxc6 20.
Bd4 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Qh4 $17 {Black's position seems more pleasant.}) ({Finally,
the attempt of repeating moves with} 15. Nf3 $2 {fails tactically due to} Nxf2
$1 16. Kxf2 Bxe3+ 17. Ke1 Qxg2 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc8g4] ;Haimovich,T (2375)
-Kobo,O (2460) ISR-ch 40th Jerusalem 2021 (4) 0-1 and Black had a winning
attack.}) 15... Qh4 16. Kg1 {The fact that we can force a repetition with Qg5
shows how comfortable is Black's position. However, it's also possible to look
for more with} Ne5 $5 {bringing more pieces to the attack. Now} 17. Nf3 {
seems a natural reply, but it allows a thematic tactical idea.} Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3
Nxf2 $1 {Things develop in a more or less forced way now:} 19. Rxf2 Bxe3 20.
Rcc2 $8 Bf5 21. Rcd2 Be4 22. g3 Qg5 $15 {I think White should be ok with
correct play here, but with two pawns up and a safer king, Black surely keeps
better practical chances.} *

